It's like humanity
works fine if you

00:44:31.990 --> 00:44:34.030
have other things in the
world, but the moment

00:44:34.030 --> 00:44:39.660
that you essentially have
a monoculture then it's

00:44:39.660 --> 00:44:42.180
harder to be human
because there's

00:44:42.180 --> 00:44:49.325
nothing else, no other scale of
reference or mode of reference.

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:55.340
All right.

00:44:55.340 --> 00:44:57.130
That's a really great question.

00:45:08.860 --> 00:45:10.950
AUDIENCE: I was curious
about the use of the word

00:45:10.950 --> 00:45:11.662
civilization.

00:45:11.662 --> 00:45:14.490
It seems to me that would have
meant something substantially

00:45:14.490 --> 00:45:16.466
different than now.

00:45:16.466 --> 00:45:19.420
When What trying
to think of what

00:45:19.420 --> 00:45:22.220
they might have meant by
it, civilizing influence

00:45:22.220 --> 00:45:26.570
is basically the
collective pressure

00:45:26.570 --> 00:45:30.990
on people to behave
less like their nature

00:45:30.990 --> 00:45:33.450
in order to get along.

00:45:33.450 --> 00:45:35.235
And it seems to me,
the more crowded

00:45:35.235 --> 00:45:39.078
we get the more
organizations dominate rather

00:45:39.078 --> 00:45:41.922
than individuals or
families dominate

00:45:41.922 --> 00:45:45.010
behavior in a town square.

00:45:45.010 --> 00:45:47.860
If it's a village it's a
few families getting along.

00:45:47.860 --> 00:45:53.902
If it's a big city there are
enormous city rule impositions

00:45:53.902 --> 00:45:56.330
controlling how things
go in that little place

00:45:56.330 --> 00:45:58.920
where a few people live around
because of all the other people

00:45:58.920 --> 00:46:01.230
who live within a mile or two.

00:46:01.230 --> 00:46:05.740
Do you see it as that
kind of, you could call it

00:46:05.740 --> 00:46:08.180
governmental pressure on
people's behavior, that's

00:46:08.180 --> 00:46:09.860
part of the problem?

00:46:09.860 --> 00:46:11.710
ROSALIND: I would
just say organized,

00:46:11.710 --> 00:46:14.480
because the organizations
can be non-governmental.

00:46:14.480 --> 00:46:17.610
They can be commercial
or whatever.

00:46:17.610 --> 00:46:21.930
Again, I think you really put
your finger on a major theme

00:46:21.930 --> 00:46:22.820
here.

00:46:22.820 --> 00:46:25.370
The word civilization,
thanks to Google,

00:46:25.370 --> 00:46:28.680
now we can go back and find
it everywhere in the past,

00:46:28.680 --> 00:46:33.070
and scholars are greatly aided
by having search engines that

00:46:33.070 --> 00:46:36.720
allow us to pull out that
word, and see where it is,

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:38.270
and see patterns, and so forth.

00:46:38.270 --> 00:46:40.940
There's also, I will say, the
Oxford English Dictionary,

00:46:40.940 --> 00:46:44.120
which gives contextual usages.

00:46:44.120 --> 00:46:46.160
So we can study that word.

00:46:46.160 --> 00:46:48.110
But you're right
that it, for them,

00:46:48.110 --> 00:46:54.080
is pointing to what is generally
a plus thing, because there's

00:46:54.080 --> 00:46:56.050
non-civilized or uncivilized.

00:46:56.050 --> 00:46:56.850
That's bad.

00:46:56.850 --> 00:47:01.220
I mean that's a word that's used
a lot in this era and even now,

00:47:01.220 --> 00:47:02.230
I mean uncivilized.

00:47:02.230 --> 00:47:03.970
So civilization is good.

00:47:03.970 --> 00:47:07.470
So for them to be saying
I am having trouble

00:47:07.470 --> 00:47:10.970
with it is somewhat rebellious.

00:47:14.240 --> 00:47:20.700
I would say that beginning in
the early 1900's there is just

00:47:20.700 --> 00:47:31.370
a fundamental disconnect
in Western civilization

00:47:31.370 --> 00:47:37.250
between a real emphasis on the
individual as having rights,

00:47:37.250 --> 00:47:42.070
and liberties, and a future, and
a story that's worth telling.

00:47:42.070 --> 00:47:45.520
This you find in romanticism,
you find in democracy,

00:47:45.520 --> 00:47:49.270
you find in the invention of
the word individualism by de

00:47:49.270 --> 00:47:52.130
Tocqueville in the 1830's.

00:47:52.130 --> 00:47:55.420
The whole romantic movement
in that large sense

00:47:55.420 --> 00:47:57.840
says you matter,
you matter a lot,

00:47:57.840 --> 00:48:00.930
and you should follow your
bliss, and write your poetry.

00:48:00.930 --> 00:48:05.840
And these romance writers
believed that and follow it.

00:48:05.840 --> 00:48:10.090
But it's the same era when the
increasing powers of humanity

00:48:10.090 --> 00:48:13.040
are creating more and
more systems, right,

00:48:13.040 --> 00:48:15.580
that constrain
individuals, and that,

00:48:15.580 --> 00:48:19.860
yes, bring progress of certain
types that are undeniable.

00:48:19.860 --> 00:48:22.550
But these two things
are happening together.

00:48:22.550 --> 00:48:25.000
And I think we still
live in a world

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:30.710
where that tension is
very real, and each of us

00:48:30.710 --> 00:48:32.390
struggles with it.

00:48:32.390 --> 00:48:36.610
The sociologist Manuel Castells
has brought this idea up

00:48:36.610 --> 00:48:40.120
to date by saying there are two
things going on in the world.

00:48:40.120 --> 00:48:42.880
This is in his trilogy
on the information age.

00:48:42.880 --> 00:48:47.430
One thing is the development of
networks which are, especially

00:48:47.430 --> 00:48:48.995
financial, but
also technological

00:48:48.995 --> 00:48:52.750
of all sorts, networks
that connect us.

00:48:52.750 --> 00:48:57.940
And there's also a quest for
identity, for self, who am I,

00:48:57.940 --> 00:49:02.740
and where do I fit, who do I
belong to, what matters to me.

00:49:02.740 --> 00:49:05.590
So Castells says
network and self.

00:49:05.590 --> 00:49:09.910
I would say romanticism, or
romance, and civilization.

00:49:09.910 --> 00:49:14.390
These are two variations on the
theme of a fundamental tension,

00:49:14.390 --> 00:49:19.500
and tensions make the world
interesting but not easy.

00:49:29.380 --> 00:49:31.874
AUDIENCE: I think there
